dpul.title: Load time for home page of Sid Lapidus DPUL Exhibit is Super Slow.

comments.body:
We ran the solr query locally on the solr box, and were finding run times of around 3 seconds. We're now not sure if that's the problem exactly, so we're going to get datadog running again and check the performance via APM.

The slow curl commands seemed to be due to text output to terminal. when we turned that off it was not slow enough to make us think solr was the issue.

Things we've investigated or thought about:

- Parent filter (for MVWs)
- The speed of solr: [APM example](https://app.datadoghq.com/apm/resource/dpul/rails.action_controller/892147145d819509?query=env%3Aproduction%20service%3Adpul%20operation_name%3Arails.action_controller%20resource_name%3A%22Spotlight%3A%3AHomePagesController%23show%22&env=production&event=AgAAAYOAE0bc4L_NnQAAAAAAAAAYAAAAAEFZT0FFMUxDQUFBb1Z0UlBUNW5CRmFBZQAAACQAAAAAMDE4MzgwMTMtNmNhNS00NTVkLWIyM2YtZWRkYTdlNGM1ZjBj&spanID=1943474858083886636&spanViewType=logs&timeHint=1664301090524&topGraphs=latency%3Alatency%2CbreakdownAs%3Apercentage%2Cerrors%3Acount%2Chits%3Acount&traceID=2206999600130823152&start=1664297740811&end=1664301340811&paused=true)
  - a curl command for timing this: https://gist.github.com/hackartisan/efd7cb381e80d0d96d719f33c0b871eb

The browse page is slower than the search results page and we're not 100% sure we're getting the browse results here. If you wanted to make sure you were getting the browse results you'd want to find a solr query for https://dpul.princeton.edu/lapidus/browse/browse-the-collection

The query times here are particularly slow and we believe it would take a rearchitecting of our indexing and retrieval process to improve them.

@kelea99 Is re-designing the exhibit home page an option? Removing the browse widget and the sidebar completely resolves the load time issue. Other widgets could be added in to showcase some of the content and/or direct users to search or browse results on a different page.

princeton_ansible.title: Verification tests on libwww report changed but do not fail

comments.body: NOTE: This behavior happens on the branch for #3366. I have not checked the main branch.

Hi,

If I follow correctly lines like these

```
TASK [test for presence libwww php ini] ****************************************
changed: [instance] => (item=upload_max_filesize = 8M)
changed: [instance] => (item=memory_limit = 256M)
```

Indicate the values the playbook is setting, correct? These are values we tweaked for various performance issues so I think we want to have the tests verify the playbook is setting them.

@kevinreiss that task shows that those values are being changed during the Verification step, which means they were NOT set during the Converge step. If the values had been set in the Converge step, the Verification playbook would return `OK` instead of `changed` for those tasks.
This probably happened when we upgraded Molecule.
